## Agents — delegate proactively

IMPORTANT: Use these subagents automatically whenever they fit — do not ask first. The main context is the scarcest resource; anything that requires reading many files or produces large output belongs in a subagent.

| Agent | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| `code-explorer` | Any codebase question that needs reading more than 3-4 files; before implementing in unfamiliar code |
| `test-runner` | Any full test/lint run — returns a condensed failure report instead of raw output |
| `workflow-coach` | The user asks how the dev workflow works or which command to use |
| `product-owner` | Judging ideas/backlog items against the vision (used by /brainstorm, /prioritize) |
| `code-reviewer` / `security-reviewer` / `architect-reviewer` | Reviewing a diff (used by /pr; also on direct request) |
| `requirements-engineer` / `tech-planner` | Structured refinement (used by /refine) |
| `test-writer` | Spec-only test creation (used by /implement Phase 1) |
| `documentation-writer` | Doc updates after implementation (used by /implement) |

Likewise, use the workflow skills (`/commit`, `/draft`, `/resume`) whenever they match the task instead of ad-hoc equivalents.

Model routing: agents pin their own model (`haiku` for mechanical work, `sonnet` for execution); planning/review agents inherit the session model. `/refine` and `/pr` ask once (supervised mode only) which tier their inherit-agents should use — session model / better-than-Sonnet (`opus`) / `sonnet` / `haiku` — and pass it as the per-invocation `model` parameter. Adjust defaults per agent in `.claude/agents/{name}.md`.

For pure "where is X?" file/symbol discovery, use the **built-in Explore agent** (Haiku) — `code-explorer` is for briefings that need judgment (patterns, pitfalls, interfaces).

## Session Behavior

If the session start context contains `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===`, immediately execute `/resume` without waiting for user input.

If `.claude/memory/settings.md` contains `unsupervised: true`:
- **Never** use `AskUserQuestion` — apply autonomous defaults from the `/unsupervised` skill
- If a hook reports `USAGE THRESHOLD REACHED`: commit the current atomic step, update the checkpoint, then run `bash .claude/hooks/usage-guard.sh --wait` (3-minute Bash timeout) repeatedly until it prints `RESUME_OK`, then continue working
- If you hit a genuine blocker (merge conflict, missing credentials, unresolvable ambiguity), write `## Blocked: <reason>` to `.claude/memory/context.md` and stop — do not wait for input
- When all work is complete, clear `## In Progress` from `.claude/memory/context.md` and stop

